{"summary": "Among various strategies for reducing impact when harvesting wild biological resources from peatlands, there is very limited evidence available. Only one strategy has been studied: reducing harvest intensity (Action ID 1744). This approach showed some positive results - a replicated, controlled study in a New Zealand bog found that Sphagnum moss cover was higher three years after harvesting when some Sphagnum was left in plots compared to complete harvesting.

The following strategies have no supporting evidence because no studies have evaluated their effects on peatland vegetation: using low impact harvesting techniques (Action ID 1745), reducing harvest frequency (Action ID 1743), using low impact vehicles for harvesting (Action ID 1746), implementing mosaic management when harvesting (Action ID 1747), allowing sustainable use of peatlands (Action ID 1801), and restricting vehicle use on peatlands (Action ID 1749).

The lack of evidence for most strategies means their effectiveness cannot be assessed based on current research.", "action_ids": ["1744", "1745", "1743", "1746", "1747", "1801", "1749"], "query": "When harvesting wild biological resources from peatlands, how do different strategies for reducing impact compare in their evidence base?"}

